04368nmm a2200613Ia 9781503638709DE-B159720240328111612.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240328t20242024cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97815036387097 a10.1515/97815036387092doi  a(DE-B1597)680252  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aHE8699.C95bJ67 2024 7aHIS0320002bisacsh04a384.5409437223/eng/202311081 aJohnston, Rosamund, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRed Tape :bRadio and Politics in Czechoslovakia, 1945-1969 /cRosamund Johnston. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (326 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStanford Studies on Central and Eastern Europe00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1 The Radio Revolution -- t2 “The Brain Becomes a Phonograph Playing a Disc over Which It Has No Control” -- t3 When Travelogues Became News -- t4 De-Stalinization Disturbs Listening -- t5 Listening in on the Neighbors -- t6 Spring in the Air? -- t7 All Together Now? -- tConclusion: From Socialist Media to Social Media -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn socialist Eastern Europe, radio simultaneously produced state power and created the conditions for it to be challenged. As the dominant form of media in Czechoslovakia from 1945 until 1969, radio constituted a site of negotiation between Communist officials, broadcast journalists, and audiences. Listeners' feedback, captured in thousands of pieces of fan mail, shows how a non-democratic society established, stabilized, and reproduced itself. In Red Tape, historian Rosamund Johnston explores the dynamic between radio reporters and the listeners who liked and trusted them while recognizing that they produced both propaganda and entertainment. Red Tape rethinks Stalinism in Czechoslovakia—one of the states in which it was at its staunchest for longest—by showing how, even then, meaningful, multi-directional communication occurred between audiences and state-controlled media. It finds de-Stalinization's first traces not in secret speeches never intended for the ears of "ordinary" listeners, but instead in earlier, changing forms of radio address. And it traces the origins of the Prague Spring's discursive climate to the censored and monitored environment of the newsroom, long before the seismic year of 1968. Bringing together European history, media studies, cultural history, and sound studies, Red Tape shows how Czechs and Slovaks used radio technologies and institutions to negotiate questions of citizenship and rights.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aCommunism and mass mediazCzechoslovakiaxHistory. 0aRadio audienceszCzechoslovakiaxHistory. 0aRadio broadcastingxPolitical aspectszCzechoslovakiaxHistory. 0aRadio journalismzCzechoslovakiaxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh  aCentral Europe.  aCold War.  aJournalism.  aPropaganda.  aRadio.  aSTS.  aSound Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079133440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363870940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503638709423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503638709/original  a978-3-11-079133-4  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aGBV-deGruyter-alles